Cursor’s engineering team (Anysphere) built the software by solving three core problems: UI control, AI orchestration, and context retrieval.

1. The Core Foundation: A Hard Fork of VS Code
Instead of writing an extension for Visual Studio Code (like GitHub Copilot historically did), Cursor is a direct fork of the open-source VS Code codebase.

Why a fork? VS Code’s extension API restricts what plugins can do. By forking the codebase, the Cursor team compiles and ships their own editor binary. This gives them low-level access to the text buffer, rendering pipeline, file explorer, and terminal.

The Benefit: It allows them to build native UI elements like inline multi-line diff overlays, fluid predictive tab completions, and custom multi-panel interfaces (like Composer) that would be architecturally impossible as a simple plugin.

The Catch: It retains 100% compatibility with your existing VS Code themes, keybindings, and extensions, though the team must manually merge upstream updates from Microsoft regularly.

2. The Context Engine (Codebase Indexing)
For an AI to give accurate answers, it needs to understand your entire project, not just the file you are looking at. Cursor handles this via a sophisticated background retrieval pipeline:

Tree-Sitter Parsing: Instead of splitting your code into random chunks by line count, Cursor uses Tree-sitter to parse your files into actual abstract syntax trees, breaking code down cleanly by function and class boundaries.

Merkle Trees for Syncing: To prevent uploading gigabytes of code constantly, Cursor uses a Merkle tree of file hashes. It tracks local changes and syncs only the modified files with their servers every few minutes.

Vector Database & Reranking: Code snippets are converted into embeddings and stored in a high-performance vector database (specifically utilizing Turbopuffer). When you ask a question or use @codebase, a fine-tuned 7B model (like a customized CodeLlama) reranks up to 500,000 tokens of context to pull the most relevant snippets.

3. High-Speed Inference (How "Cursor Tab" is so fast)
One of Cursor's biggest technical feats is generating code completions before your next keystroke makes them obsolete. They achieve this using a concept called Speculative Edits/Decoding:

Draft Tokens: When you edit code, most of the file stays exactly the same. Cursor uses your existing source code as "draft tokens."

Parallel Processing: Instead of generating code token-by-token from scratch, their custom inference backend feeds the chunks of your existing file to a large model (like a 70B model) in parallel. The model accepts the unchanged chunks in bulk and only generates new tokens where it predicts a change, pushing speeds up to ~1,000 tokens/second (a massive speedup over traditional LLM generation).

Rapid Reinforcement Learning: Their completion models are retrained every 90 minutes via a reinforcement learning loop based on what suggestions developers accept or reject globally, deploying multiple checkpoints a day.

4. Prompt Engineering via "Priompt"
Managing what goes into an LLM prompt when you have a 272,000-token context window is highly complex. Cursor open-sourced a framework called Priompt (Priority Prompt) to handle this.

Priompt compiles prompts using JSX components where every piece of data (e.g., open files, lint errors, git diffs) is assigned a priority score.

If the combined context exceeds the model's token limit, Priompt uses a binary search algorithm to instantly drop the lowest-priority elements, ensuring the model always gets the absolute best context available without breaking.

5. Agentic Workflows (Composer & Cloud Agents)
Cursor includes advanced multi-file editing workflows like Composer and Agent Mode.

Instead of editing a single line, these features use specialized AI orchestration layers to plan an architecture change (e.g., "add a JWT authentication system").

The agent maps out dependencies, spawns isolated background VMs to test code, runs terminal commands, and edits multiple files simultaneously while checking for breaking changes across service boundaries.